  "description": "Currying is the transformation of a function that takes multiple arguments into a sequence of functions, each taking a single argument. A function f(a,b,c)f(a, b, c) becomes a function f(a)f(a) that returns a function g(b)g(b) that returns a function h(c)h(c) that produces the result. In notation:\nf:A×B×C→D⟶f′:A→(B→(C→D)) f : A \\times B \\times C \\to D \\quad\\longrightarrow\\quad f\u0026#x27; : A \\to (B \\to (C \\to D)) The concept is named after Haskell Curry, though it was first described by Moses Schönfinkel. In the lambda calculus, all functions naturally take a single argument — multi-argument functions are always expressed as curried chains of single-argument abstractions. The expression λx. λy. x+y\\lambda x.\\, \\lambda y.\\, x + y takes xx and returns a function that takes yy and returns x+yx + y.\n",
